# installing packages and modules
import pandas as pd # to set up dataframes
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt # for plotting barcharts, histograms and piecharts
import numpy as np # to create arrays and matrices
import seaborn as sns # to plot correlation heatmap
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler  # for standardising dataset
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split  # for splitting into train and test dataset
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE  # Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique for oversampling minority class
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor  # to compute VIF for each feature

# converting qualitative categorical fields (i.e. Attrition_Flag, Gender, Education_Level, Marital_Status, Income_Category, Card_Category) to numerical
# Attrition_Flag - Existing Customer set to 0, Attrited Customer set to 1
df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Attrition_Flag"] == "Existing Customer", "Attrition_Flag"] = 0
df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Attrition_Flag"] == "Attrited Customer", "Attrition_Flag"] = 1

# Gender - M set to 0, F set to 1
df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Gender"] == "M", "Gender"] = 0
df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Gender"] == "F", "Gender"] = 1

# Education_Level - Uneducated to 0, High School to 1, College to 2, Graduate to 3, Post-Graduate to 4, Doctorate to 5
education_labels = ["Uneducated", "High School", "College", "Graduate", "Post-Graduate", "Doctorate"]
education_tags = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
for i in range(len(education_labels)):
    df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Education_Level"] == education_labels[i], "Education_Level"] = education_tags[i]

# Marital_Status - Single to 0, Married to 1, Divorced to 2
married_labels = ["Single", "Married", "Divorced"]
married_tags = [0, 1, 2]
for i in range(len(married_labels)):
    df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Marital_Status"] == married_labels[i], "Marital_Status"] = married_tags[i]

# Income_Category - take average income of that category
# for "Less than $40K" category, set income as 20000
# for "$120K +" category, set income as 150000
income_labels = ["Less than $40K", "$40K - $60K", "$60K - $80K", "$80K - $120K", "$120K +"]
income_tags = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]
for i in range(len(income_labels)):
    df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Income_Category"] == income_labels[i], "Income_Category"] = income_tags[i]

# Card_Category - Blue to 0, Silver to 1, Gold to 2, Platinum to 3
card_labels = ["Blue", "Silver", "Gold", "Platinum"]
card_tags = [0, 1, 2, 3]
for i in range(len(card_labels)):
    df_clean_1.loc[df_clean_1["Card_Category"] == card_labels[i], "Card_Category"] = card_tags[i]

categorical_fields = ["Attrition_Flag", "Gender", "Education_Level", "Marital_Status", "Income_Category", "Card_Category"]
# iterating over features and plotting a boxplot + histogram if it's a non-categorical feature
for col in df_clean_1:
    if col not in categorical_fields:
        plt.boxplot(df_clean_1[col], meanline=True, vert=False)
        plt.title("{0} Distribution".format(col))
        plt.show()
        plt.hist(df_clean_1[col])
        plt.show()
    else:
#         if not, plot a pie chart
        categories = df[col].unique()
        categories_for_col = []
        for i in range(len(categories)):
            if categories[i] != "Unknown":
                categories_for_col.append(categories[i])
        counts_col = [counts for counts in df_clean_1.groupby(col).count().iloc[:,0]]
        plt.pie(counts_col, labels=categories_for_col, autopct="%.2f%%")

Data Processing Round 2: Using SMOTE to oversample the minority class¶

In [12]:
# splitting to labels and features
training_class = training_set.iloc[:, 0]
training_class = training_class.astype("category")
training_features = training_set.iloc[:,1:]
# training_features.head(5)

# use smote to oversample the minority class (i.e. Attrited Customer)
# generate more instances of attrited customers - sampling_strategy = 0.5 means our resulting dataset should have 2984 attrited customers (2984 = 50% of Existing Customers)
over_sample = SMOTE(sampling_strategy = 0.5)
training_features_smote, training_class_smote = over_sample.fit_resample(training_features, training_class)

# checking number of datapoints before and after resampling
print("Number of datapoints before resampling: {0}".format(len(training_features)))
print("Number of datapoints after resampling: {0}".format(len(training_features_smote)))

EDA 4: Correlation Heatmap of Features¶

In [16]:
# plotting lower triangle of the correlation matrix on a heatmap
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(training_features_smote.corr(), dtype=np.bool))
plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Features")
heatmap = sns.heatmap(training_features_smote.corr(), mask=mask, vmin=-1, vmax=1, cmap="seismic", annot=True)
# reasons for high correlation:
# credit_limit and avg_open_to_buy: avg_open_to_buy = credit_limit - total_revolving_bal
# avg_utilization_rate and credit_limit: avg_utilization_rate = total_revolving_bal/credit_limit => as credit_limit increases, avg_utilization_rate decreases
# avg_utilization_rate and total_revolving_bal: avg_utilization_rate = total_revolving_bal/credit_limit => as total_revolving_bal increases, avg_utilization_rate increases
# avg_utilization_rate and avg_open_to_buy: avg_utilization_rate = total_revolving_bal/credit_limit = (credit_limit - avg_open_to_buy)/credit_limit => as avg_open_to_buy increases, avg_utilization_rate decreases
# income_category and credit_limit: higher the income, larger the amount of credit that will be offered
# income_category and card_category: higher the income results, the more eligible the person is to higher tiered products
# income_category and avg_open_to_buy: avg_open_to_buy = credit_limit - total_revolving_bal and income_category is correlated to credit_limit
# card_category and credit_limit: higher tiered cards likely have larger credit limits as well
# card_category and avg_open_to_buy: avg_open_to_buy = credit_limit - total_revolving_bal and card_category is correlated to credit_limit
# total_transaction_ct and total_transaction_amt: assuming average transaction amount remains constant per transaction, more transactions = increase in total transaction amount
# total_ct_chng_q4_q1 and total_amt_chg_q4_q1: change measured by difference in total transaction counts and total transaction amount, if change in total transaction counts increases then change in change in total transaction amount also increases, assuming average transaction amount remains constant

EDA 5: VIF by Features¶

In [18]:
# store feature names
col_names = []
for col in training_features_smote:
    col_names.append(col)

# compute and store vif for each feature
training_features_smote_array = training_features_smote.to_numpy(dtype=float)
vif_values = []
for i in range(len(col_names)):
    vif = variance_inflation_factor(training_features_smote_array, i)
#     if vif == inf:
#         vif = 20
    vif_values.append(vif)
    print("{0} VIF = {1}".format(col_names[i], vif))

# given that Credit_Limit, Total_Revolving_Bal and Avg_Open_To_Buy are all dependent (i.e. Credit_Limit = Total_Revolving_Bal + Avg_Open_To_Buy), VIF is unbounded
# remove Avg_Open_To_Buy as it can be inferred from the Credit_Limit and Total_Revolving_Bal and is the systemic difference between Credit_Limit and Total_Revolving_Bal

    col_names.append(col)

    vif_revised = variance_inflation_factor(training_features_smote_array, i)

plt.ylabel("VIF")
plt.title("VIF by Feature")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
